ARTICLE.TITLE: 'Large scale' Black Lives Matter march planned to take place in Nottingham this weekend
ARTICLE.TEXT:
Want the best Nottingham news by 9am every day? Sign up to our newsletter! Subscribe Thank you for subscribing We have more newsletters Show me See our privacy notice Invalid Email

A 'large scale' Black Lives Matter march is planned to take place in Nottingham city centre this weekend.

Nottingham United Against Racism will be holding a march in support of anti-racism and Black Lives Matter on Saturday, August 15 at 12noon.

It has been described as a 'large scale march' and will start in Old Market Square where there will be introductory speeches and an open mic for people to protest against racism in the UK and share their experiences.

The march will then proceed down Alfreton Road to Radford Police Station, where there will be a short stop for "people to gather and chant."

The protesters will then move up to HMP Nottingham to show "their support for the unfairly imprisoned within the walls."

Organisers are asking that attendants practice social distancing, wear masks, and bring their own water.

(Image: Matt Jarram)

Nottingham United Against Racism will be circulating a petition during the march, demanding an end to the following - deportations, stop and search and joint enterprise.

They are also seeking for police to release IPP prisoners and for recall to be stopped from 99 years to two years.

A spokeswoman for Nottingham United Against Racism said: "The latest wave of anti-racists protests sprang up in response to the brutal murder of George Floyd at the hands of US police, and spread to other countries around the world.

"In Nottingham, local protesters called for a BLM event in the Forest Rec on June 7, which was attended by over a thousand people.

"Since then, further events in support have taken place in Nottingham.

"From June 20 a weekly open mic has been held every Saturday at 12pm in the Market Square, where members of the public are invited to use their voices to take a stand against racism.

"Support has grown weekly, with the protests typically culminating in spontaneous marches to police stations and courts in the area.

"The message is clear: Black Lives Matter is not a trend. It’s a persistent social movement that refuses to accept any longer the endemic racism and systemic inequality that pervades Great Britain."
